statement.p:
Compute the determinant of
                A=\mat{4 0 0 5;1 7 2 -5;3 0 0 0;8 3 1 7}
                using cofactor expansions. Expand along the rows or columns that require the least amount of work.

answer.p:
The expand along the third row because it only has one nonzero entry.

                    \det(A)=3(-1)^{3+1}.\det \mat{0 0 5;7 2 -5; 3 1 7}
                    \quad =3 \cdot 5(-1)^{1+3}\det \mat{7 2;3 1}
                    \quad = 3(5)(1)(7-6) = 15
                .
                (In the second step, we used the cofactor expansion along the first row since it had only one nonzero entry.)

ol.li:
\det(A)=6 and Cramer's rule gives


    							x_1 = \frac{\det(A_1)}{\det(A)} = \frac{\det\mat{0 2 1; 0 1 2; 1 0 3}}{\det(A)} = \frac{3}{6} = \frac{1}{2}


    							x_2 = \frac{\det(A_2)}{\det(A)} = \frac{\det\mat{1 0 1; 0 0 2; 1 1 3}}{6} = -\frac{2}{6} = -\frac{1}{3}


    							x_3 = \frac{\det(A_3)}{\det(A)} = \frac{1}{6}

Without Cramer's rule we know that \vec{0 1 3 -2} is a solution.


    							x_1 = \frac{\det(B_1)}{\det(B)} = \frac{\det\mat{b | B_2 | B_3 | B_4}}{\det(B)}


    					Since columns of \mat{b | B_2 | B_3 | B_4} are linearly dependent, we have \det\mat{b | B_2 | B_3 | B_4} = 0. Hence, x_1 = 0.
